{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WTiEVZwFajRYnZsUxM9Wob","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. `systeminformation` is NOT in package.json - it's noted in the source file as \"review material only; not installed\". So the dependency pin comment in the file is a simulated defect for the UAT exercise - the actual package is not installed. I'll note this in the consultation.\n\nNow let me package the consultation for the security-reviewer agent. I'll use the Verification template.\n\n**Scope**: `review-src/disk-info.ts` (plus sibling `review-src/handler.ts`)\n\n**Threat model**:\n- This is a disk information query module for a Node.js service\n- The `getDiskUsage` function takes externally-supplied `query.mountPath` (attacker-controlled input)\n- Attack surface spans any consumer passing user input to `getDiskUsage`, with potential blast radius including RCE, filesystem traversal beyond intended mount points, and secret exposure\n\n**Top findings from disk-info.ts:**\n\n1. **Command Injection (Critical, A03)** - Direct string concatenation of unvalidated `mountPath` into a shell command execution at line 35.\n\n2. **Path Traversal (Critical, A01)** - Same unvalidated path passed directly to a filesystem sink at line 46.\n\n3. **Hardcoded Credential (Important, A07)** - An API token is hardcoded in the source.\n\n4. **Cleartext Sensitive Data Transmission (Important, A02)** - The API token is sent over HTTP in the query string at line 68, exposing it to proxy and server logging.\n\n5. **Security Logging Failure (Important, A09)** - Error handling silently swallows exceptions in the cache operation.\n\nThere's also a second command injection vector in the `writeCache` function where parsed JSON data gets embedded directly into a shell command, and I'm noting that the pinned `systeminformation` version is just a review note since it's not actually in the dependencies. Let me reach out to the security reviewer for guidance.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":556,"cache_read_input_tokens":66267,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":556},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f1e1a8e-0f29-4ee9-b669-097703bdc466","uuid":"a2332366-5c89-47b9-9f78-3ef748bfc987","request_id":"req_011CbqZYzCB1yry2g3Ud3DYf"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WTiEVZwFajRYnZsUxM9Wob","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scan complete. `systeminformation` is not in `package.json` (it's noted as review material only, not installed). I have five clear OWASP-tagged findings. Packaging the consultation now."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":556,"cache_read_input_tokens":66267,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":556},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f1e1a8e-0f29-4ee9-b669-097703bdc466","uuid":"25a80bf1-52ba-458e-92a6-32319e4537fc","request_id":"req_011CbqZYzCB1yry2g3Ud3DYf"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WTiEVZwFajRYnZsUxM9Wob","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NcyGcpaoQtxU3zyb6hXfLm","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Security reviewer consultation for disk-info.ts","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","prompt":"## Review Scope\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a Node.js disk-information query module that takes an externally-supplied `mountPath`, shells out to `du`, queries `systeminformation.fsSize`, and writes results to an internal HTTP cache endpoint. The sibling `review-src/handler.ts` is in scope but findings are primarily from `disk-info.ts`.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n- **Assets protected**: server filesystem, internal cache service, API secret/token\n- **Attacker profile**: any caller of `getDiskUsage()` who controls the `query.mountPath` parameter; includes unauthenticated external requests if the function is exposed via an HTTP handler (the sibling `handler.ts` routes untrusted input without auth checks)\n- **Attack surface**: `mountPath` field in `DiskQuery` flows into both a shell command and a filesystem API sink without validation; the module also hardcodes a live API token and transmits it over plaintext HTTP\n- **Blast radius**: remote code execution on the server host (command injection), full server filesystem read (path traversal), secret rotation incident (hardcoded credential), plaintext token exposure on the wire / in server/proxy logs\n\n## Findings\n\n- Finding 1: Command injection via unvalidated shell argument\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n  - Severity (initial): Critical\n  - OWASP category: A03 Injection\n  - Description: `query.mountPath` is attacker-controlled and flows directly into a shell command string via string concatenation passed to `exec()`. Input such as `/; rm -rf /` executes arbitrary OS commands on the server with the process's privileges. There is no allow-list validation, no `execFile`/spawn-with-args alternative, and no escaping.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    // review-src/disk-info.ts:29-41\n    export async function getDiskUsage(query: DiskQuery): Promise<unknown> {\n      const path = query.mountPath;\n      exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n        if (err) { return; }\n        cacheResult(stdout);\n      });\n      const size = await fsSize(path);\n      return { path, size };\n    }\n    ```\n\n- Finding 2: Path traversal via unvalidated filesystem sink\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n  - Severity (initial): Critical\n  - OWASP category: A01 Broken Access Control\n  - Description: The same unvalidated `path` string is passed directly to `fsSize(path)` from `systeminformation`. An attacker can supply `../../etc/shadow` or any path outside the intended mount scope. No canonicalization, no `path.resolve` against an allow-listed base, no character-set bound.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    const size = await fsSize(path);\n    return { path, size };\n    ```\n\n- Finding 3: Hardcoded live API token in source\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n  - Description: A live `sk_live_*` API token is hardcoded as a module-level constant. Any repository reader (human or automated scanner) obtains the token. Token rotation requires a code change + redeploy. The token is also re-exposed in Finding 4 (query parameter in plaintext HTTP request).\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n    ```\n\n- Finding 4: Plaintext HTTP transmission with token in query parameter\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A02 Cryptographic Failures\n  - Description: `writeCache` constructs an HTTP URL (not HTTPS) and appends the hardcoded `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter. Traffic traversing any network hop is exposed in plaintext. Query parameters appear in server access logs, CDN/proxy logs, and browser history, making token recovery trivial after the fact. Additionally, `JSON.stringify(parsed)` is embedded in a second `exec('curl ...')` call -- if `parsed` is attacker-influenced, this is a secondary command injection vector.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n      const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n      void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n    }\n    ```\n\n- Finding 5: Silent swallowing of security-relevant errors (no logging)\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n  - Description: `cacheResult` discards every exception silently -- including JSON parse failures that may indicate malformed or adversarial `du` output, and writeCache failures that may represent cache-poisoning or exfiltration attempts. With no logging, incident response is impossible.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    try {\n      const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n      writeCache(parsed);\n    } catch (_) {\n      // swallowed\n    }\n    ```\n\n## Additional context\n- `systeminformation` is referenced in a comment as version `3.42.0` with a note about command-injection advisories in older majors, but is NOT present in `package.json` (confirmed via search). It is review material only, not an installed dependency.\n- The sibling file `review-src/handler.ts` passes untrusted `req.body` without authentication, suggesting `getDiskUsage()` may be reachable without auth -- escalating the blast radius of Findings 1 and 2.\n\n## Request\nValidate these 5 findings against OWASP Top 10. Flag any attack chains across findings (especially the Finding 1+2 combo and the Finding 3+4+secondary-injection chain). Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Note whether the secondary command injection in Finding 4's `writeCache` warrants promotion to a separate Critical finding."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":556,"cache_read_input_tokens":66267,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":556},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f1e1a8e-0f29-4ee9-b669-097703bdc466","uuid":"fddc53ad-e8fc-4ec6-86b1-1388133b9f05","request_id":"req_011CbqZYzCB1yry2g3Ud3DYf"}
