{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NcyGcpaoQtxU3zyb6hXfLm","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All findings confirmed against source. The secondary injection in Finding 4 warrants a separate Critical (distinct sink, distinct vector per FIX-2). Finding 5's handler defects add an unauthenticated reachability + crash surface.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker-controlled `query.mountPath` into a shell string (RCE, e.g. `/; rm -rf /`). Use `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])`.\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] `writeCache` builds `exec('curl ' + url ... + JSON.stringify(parsed))` from `du`-derived `parsed` (second-order command injection). Use `execFile` / `fetch` with arg array.\n\n### Important\n\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `path` passed to `fsSize` enables traversal (`../../etc/shadow`). `path.resolve` against an allow-listed base; reject escapes.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A07] live `sk_live_*` token hardcoded as `API_TOKEN`; any repo reader obtains it, rotation needs redeploy. Move to env/secret store; rotate now.\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] `writeCache` posts `API_TOKEN` over `http://` in a query param, leaking it on-wire and in proxy/access logs. Use https; move token to header.\n7. review-src/handler.ts:17: [A04] unguarded `JSON.parse(req.body)` on untrusted body crashes handler via `SyntaxError` (DoS). Wrap in try/catch; return 400.\n8. review-src/handler.ts:21: [A01] `payload.admin === true` self-asserts admin role from request body (privilege escalation). Derive role from authenticated session, not payload.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:58: [A09] `catch (_)` in `cacheResult` swallows parse/cache failures with no logging, blinding incident response. Log error with context before discarding.\n\n### Questions\n\n9. review-src/handler.ts:13: [A01] is `handleRequest` mounted behind auth middleware? If unauthenticated, Findings 1, 2, 6, 8 are all remotely reachable by anonymous callers.\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 6: raised to Critical (initial: noted as secondary within Finding 4). Distinct sink (line 69 vs token-leak at 68) and distinct vector warrant a separate Critical per one-issue-per-finding. `parsed` derives from `du` stdout, itself influenced by the injectable `mountPath`, so the chain is reachable.\n\nValidation of Finding 8: not in the original 5; `payload.admin` trust is a body-driven privilege-escalation distinct from handler.ts crash defects. Important pending auth context (Finding 9); Critical if endpoint is unauthenticated.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 1+2 share one root: `mountPath` reaches both a shell and an fs sink unvalidated, so a single crafted input yields both RCE and arbitrary read. Findings 1->6 chain: `mountPath` injection poisons `du` stdout, which flows through `JSON.parse` into the second `exec` (`writeCache`), a second execution path. Findings 3+4 compound: the hardcoded secret is then broadcast in plaintext, turning a static leak into a wire/log leak. Finding 9 is the force multiplier: if `handler.ts` routes `req.body` to `getDiskUsage` without auth (Findings 7, 8 confirm no auth checks), every Critical becomes unauthenticated-remote, and Finding 8's body-trusted `admin` flag gives anonymous callers the admin path.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\n`review-src/handler.ts:35` `processAdmin` returns full `payload` as admin data; if reachable via Finding 8, it is an unauthenticated data-reflection surface worth scanning."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: af072efd5d6cb8f80 (use SendMessage with to: 'af072efd5d6cb8f80' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 38000\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 25061</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f1e1a8e-0f29-4ee9-b669-097703bdc466","uuid":"a3af79f9-31d0-4532-b0bf-7ebcf70c7342","timestamp":"2026-06-08T09:34:05.777Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"## Review Scope\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a Node.js disk-information query module that takes an externally-supplied `mountPath`, shells out to `du`, queries `systeminformation.fsSize`, and writes results to an internal HTTP cache endpoint. The sibling `review-src/handler.ts` is in scope but findings are primarily from `disk-info.ts`.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n- **Assets protected**: server filesystem, internal cache service, API secret/token\n- **Attacker profile**: any caller of `getDiskUsage()` who controls the `query.mountPath` parameter; includes unauthenticated external requests if the function is exposed via an HTTP handler (the sibling `handler.ts` routes untrusted input without auth checks)\n- **Attack surface**: `mountPath` field in `DiskQuery` flows into both a shell command and a filesystem API sink without validation; the module also hardcodes a live API token and transmits it over plaintext HTTP\n- **Blast radius**: remote code execution on the server host (command injection), full server filesystem read (path traversal), secret rotation incident (hardcoded credential), plaintext token exposure on the wire / in server/proxy logs\n\n## Findings\n\n- Finding 1: Command injection via unvalidated shell argument\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n  - Severity (initial): Critical\n  - OWASP category: A03 Injection\n  - Description: `query.mountPath` is attacker-controlled and flows directly into a shell command string via string concatenation passed to `exec()`. Input such as `/; rm -rf /` executes arbitrary OS commands on the server with the process's privileges. There is no allow-list validation, no `execFile`/spawn-with-args alternative, and no escaping.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    // review-src/disk-info.ts:29-41\n    export async function getDiskUsage(query: DiskQuery): Promise<unknown> {\n      const path = query.mountPath;\n      exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n        if (err) { return; }\n        cacheResult(stdout);\n      });\n      const size = await fsSize(path);\n      return { path, size };\n    }\n    ```\n\n- Finding 2: Path traversal via unvalidated filesystem sink\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n  - Severity (initial): Critical\n  - OWASP category: A01 Broken Access Control\n  - Description: The same unvalidated `path` string is passed directly to `fsSize(path)` from `systeminformation`. An attacker can supply `../../etc/shadow` or any path outside the intended mount scope. No canonicalization, no `path.resolve` against an allow-listed base, no character-set bound.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    const size = await fsSize(path);\n    return { path, size };\n    ```\n\n- Finding 3: Hardcoded live API token in source\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n  - Description: A live `sk_live_*` API token is hardcoded as a module-level constant. Any repository reader (human or automated scanner) obtains the token. Token rotation requires a code change + redeploy. The token is also re-exposed in Finding 4 (query parameter in plaintext HTTP request).\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n    ```\n\n- Finding 4: Plaintext HTTP transmission with token in query parameter\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A02 Cryptographic Failures\n  - Description: `writeCache` constructs an HTTP URL (not HTTPS) and appends the hardcoded `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter. Traffic traversing any network hop is exposed in plaintext. Query parameters appear in server access logs, CDN/proxy logs, and browser history, making token recovery trivial after the fact. Additionally, `JSON.stringify(parsed)` is embedded in a second `exec('curl ...')` call -- if `parsed` is attacker-influenced, this is a secondary command injection vector.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n      const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n      void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n    }\n    ```\n\n- Finding 5: Silent swallowing of security-relevant errors (no logging)\n  - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60`\n  - Severity (initial): Important\n  - OWASP category: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n  - Description: `cacheResult` discards every exception silently -- including JSON parse failures that may indicate malformed or adversarial `du` output, and writeCache failures that may represent cache-poisoning or exfiltration attempts. With no logging, incident response is impossible.\n  - Code context:\n    ```ts\n    try {\n      const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n      writeCache(parsed);\n    } catch (_) {\n      // swallowed\n    }\n    ```\n\n## Additional context\n- `systeminformation` is referenced in a comment as version `3.42.0` with a note about command-injection advisories in older majors, but is NOT present in `package.json` (confirmed via search). It is review material only, not an installed dependency.\n- The sibling file `review-src/handler.ts` passes untrusted `req.body` without authentication, suggesting `getDiskUsage()` may be reachable without auth -- escalating the blast radius of Findings 1 and 2.\n\n## Request\nValidate these 5 findings against OWASP Top 10. Flag any attack chains across findings (especially the Finding 1+2 combo and the Finding 3+4+secondary-injection chain). Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Note whether the secondary command injection in Finding 4's `writeCache` warrants promotion to a separate Critical finding.","agentId":"af072efd5d6cb8f80","agentType":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All findings confirmed against source. The secondary injection in Finding 4 warrants a separate Critical (distinct sink, distinct vector per FIX-2). Finding 5's handler defects add an unauthenticated reachability + crash surface.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker-controlled `query.mountPath` into a shell string (RCE, e.g. `/; rm -rf /`). Use `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])`.\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] `writeCache` builds `exec('curl ' + url ... + JSON.stringify(parsed))` from `du`-derived `parsed` (second-order command injection). Use `execFile` / `fetch` with arg array.\n\n### Important\n\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `path` passed to `fsSize` enables traversal (`../../etc/shadow`). `path.resolve` against an allow-listed base; reject escapes.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A07] live `sk_live_*` token hardcoded as `API_TOKEN`; any repo reader obtains it, rotation needs redeploy. Move to env/secret store; rotate now.\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] `writeCache` posts `API_TOKEN` over `http://` in a query param, leaking it on-wire and in proxy/access logs. Use https; move token to header.\n7. review-src/handler.ts:17: [A04] unguarded `JSON.parse(req.body)` on untrusted body crashes handler via `SyntaxError` (DoS). Wrap in try/catch; return 400.\n8. review-src/handler.ts:21: [A01] `payload.admin === true` self-asserts admin role from request body (privilege escalation). Derive role from authenticated session, not payload.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:58: [A09] `catch (_)` in `cacheResult` swallows parse/cache failures with no logging, blinding incident response. Log error with context before discarding.\n\n### Questions\n\n9. review-src/handler.ts:13: [A01] is `handleRequest` mounted behind auth middleware? If unauthenticated, Findings 1, 2, 6, 8 are all remotely reachable by anonymous callers.\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 6: raised to Critical (initial: noted as secondary within Finding 4). Distinct sink (line 69 vs token-leak at 68) and distinct vector warrant a separate Critical per one-issue-per-finding. `parsed` derives from `du` stdout, itself influenced by the injectable `mountPath`, so the chain is reachable.\n\nValidation of Finding 8: not in the original 5; `payload.admin` trust is a body-driven privilege-escalation distinct from handler.ts crash defects. Important pending auth context (Finding 9); Critical if endpoint is unauthenticated.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 1+2 share one root: `mountPath` reaches both a shell and an fs sink unvalidated, so a single crafted input yields both RCE and arbitrary read. Findings 1->6 chain: `mountPath` injection poisons `du` stdout, which flows through `JSON.parse` into the second `exec` (`writeCache`), a second execution path. Findings 3+4 compound: the hardcoded secret is then broadcast in plaintext, turning a static leak into a wire/log leak. Finding 9 is the force multiplier: if `handler.ts` routes `req.body` to `getDiskUsage` without auth (Findings 7, 8 confirm no auth checks), every Critical becomes unauthenticated-remote, and Finding 8's body-trusted `admin` flag gives anonymous callers the admin path.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\n`review-src/handler.ts:35` `processAdmin` returns full `payload` as admin data; if reachable via Finding 8, it is an unauthenticated data-reflection surface worth scanning."}],"totalDurationMs":25061,"totalTokens":38000,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2520,"cache_read_input_tokens":34092,"output_tokens":1386,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2520},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":2,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
